Limitation applied to requirement(s) or to the concept(s) the requirement is about. Additional Information: An example in eProcurement, a threshold: the minimum Turnover required by the buyer to select the candidates.

A condition for evaluation or assessment. Additional Information: In general, criteria are used for comparison, filtering and selection. Criteria usually set minimum constraints (e.g. limits, intervals, thresholds, etc.) that need to be met in order to pass the required conditions or to fulfil them in a certain degree or quality. The evaluation of the fulfilment is usually supported with the provision of evidences.

documentation.value: Relative importance assigned to a given criterion. Source: ePO
The explanation of how the weighting of a Criterion is to be used at evaluation time. Additional Information: Normally used for transparency matters. Source: ESPD and ePO

The numeric form used to weight. Additional Information: Typically these forms are decimal or percentage. However some business domains provide long lists of other types of weighing. See for example the codelist number-weight used in eForms1. Source: based on ESPD and EU Vocabularies. 1 eForms: https://ec.europa.eu/growth/single-market/public-procurement/digital/eforms_en.

Additional parameter used to adjust the evaluation of the criterion composed of multiple sub-criteria. Additional Information: In neural networks, the bias is equivalent to an intercept added in a linear equation used to shift the activation function to either right or left. It can be also used to manually adjust the pass/fail calculation of a weighted criterion.

properties.documentation: A reference to a concrete manifestation of a document, or the content of the document itself.

documentation.value: The document's content embedded as binary object (Base64).
The status of a document content.
A code used to identify the role played by this document.

properties.documentation: The data proving that a requirement is met or has been fulfilled. Additional Information: Evidences are usually references to a record, or the record content itself, used to prove the veracity of a requirement fulfilment. The concept of 'record' herein is to be understood as it used for records management: a digital object that is considered final (e.g. not a working document) and cannot be altered. Examples of evidences can be a stream of data value or values provided by a base registry, a structured official e-certificate issued by a public authority, an unstructured document (e.g. a PDF) provided by an authorised service provider acting on behalf of an authority, other. Source: based on the ePO definition of Evidence.

documentation.value: The security classification assigned to an Evidence or, in general, to a content.
A code identifying an exception when trying to provide an evidence (e.g. from a Data Service).

properties.documentation: Information about the characteristics of an expected evidence, such as the desired content, format, source, etc.

documentation.value: A classification code to specify the layout and content expected for an evidence.

A classification code use to specify the machine-readability of a content. Additional information In the CCCEV this is used to indicate whether the types of evidences required will contain structured data or not.

properties.documentation: A collection of types of evidences. Additional information The respondent of a Requirement for which one or more types of evidences have been specified in an EvidenceTypeList is expected to provide Evidence(s) conformant to that type of evidence. This list is use to build "combinations" of assets; e.g., in a Request for Evidences you could have: List-1: EvidencType-1 AND EvidenceType-2 AND EvidenceType-3; OR List-2: EvidencType-1 AND EvidenceType-5 AND EvidenceType-4;

documentation.value: A unique value, in the context of use, assigned to the instance of this property or to one of its subproperties.
The preferred label used to identify the instance of this class or of one of its subclasses.
A short explanation about the nature, attributes, uses or any other additional information that helps clarify the understanding of the concept being instantiated.

properties.documentation:
A request for data that is proof of evidence or leads to the source of such a proof.
Additional Information:
The response to an information requirement is an evidence when the issuer of the response is an authoritative source (a.k.a. source of truth, e.g. a Civil Registry providing data about a natural person for the provision of public service through the Single Digital Gateway). In other cases the responses might not be issued by an authoritative source but the issuer supports the responses with evidences (or commits to support them timely, e.g. a self-declaration or a declaration of oath).

A source from where requirements are identified and drawn. Additional Information Usual reference frameworks are legal and non-legal specifications. Examples of reference frameworks can be, the ELI Legal Resources used for the BREG catalogue of datasets, the basis for the ISA2 CAMSS Scenarios such as the Regulation (EU) 1025/2012 or the EIF Framework, the European Directives used in e-Certis and the ESPD Implementing Regulation for the identification of exclusion grounds and selection criteria, a standard, a technical specification, etc.

A condition demanded. Additional Information: Generic class representing any type of prerequisite that may be desired, needed or imposed as an obligation. The European Directive on services in the internal market1 defines requirement as any obligation, prohibition, condition or limit provided for in exercise of their legal autonomy [..]. Source: based on the Collins English Dictionary, accessed through TheFreeDictionary.com hub.------------------------- 1 See Directive 2006/123/EU, Article 4(7), Requirements.: https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32006L0123&from=EN.

A short explanation about the nature, attributes, uses or any other additional information that helps clarify the understanding of the concept being instantiated.

The identifier representing the division within a system of classification to which the instance of this class belongs. Additional information The classification system is normally a controlled vocabulary (e.g. a codelist or a taxonomy) the use of which is commonly agreed by a community of users in the context of a business or problem domain. Source: based on sense #2 of the Merriam-Webster English dictionary.

properties.documentation: A datum. Additional information In the CCCEV the datum is always associated (or referred) to a concept defined in a specific namespace. The namespace is expected to de-referenceable and to provide the definition and type of the datum.

documentation.value: A monetary value, with the indication of the currency, provided as the response to a required concept.
A code identifier provided as the response to a required concept.
A date provided as the response to a required concept.

A Boolean value (true or false) provided as the response to a required concept.
A measure, and the unit of the measure, provided as the response to a required concept.

A number of items provided as the response to a required concept.
A text provided as the response to a required concept.
The time (hh:mm:ss) provided as the response to a required concept.
A Uniform Resource Identifier provided as the response to a required concept.
A code used to identify a user-defined data type.
A text with the signature of a method (e.g. a Java function, or an endpoint call) provided as the response to a required concept.
A code identifying an exception when trying to provide an answer to a required concept.

properties.documentation: A reference to an entity, i.e. a class or a property, which is defined in a known ontology or vocabulary. Additional information: A concept defined in the context of a Requirement must be unambiguous so there is no possibility of misinterpretation. Hence the use of qualified names (a pair {namespace, local name} is strongly recommended for the identification of the entity being referred to.

Additional information The classification system is normally a controlled vocabulary (e.g. a codelist or a taxonomy) the use of which is commonly agreed by a community of users in the context of a business or problem domain. Source: based on sense #2 of the Merriam-Webster English dictionary.
The preferred label used to identify the instance of this class or of one of its subclasses.
A short explanation about the nature, attributes, uses or any other additional information that helps clarify the understanding of the concept being instantiated.

Standing for qualified name. Mechanism used to identify concisely and unambiguously an entity, i.e. a class or a property. Additional information Qualified names are pairs of {namespace URI, entity local name} where the namespace URI is usually replaced by a prefix, as in cccev:Criterion, xsd:int, or dcat:Dataset. Source: based on the W3C definition of QNames for XML.

A sub-requirement with more granular detail(s) or of different nature. Additional Information An example of granular sub-requirements can be a criterion defining more specific sub-criteria. Different examples can be found in different domains and situations. Thus, in the domain of e-Procurement EU exclusion criteria (a.k.a. grounds for exclusion), national criteria are implemented as sub-criteria hierarchically descending from an EU parent criterion. Neural networks can also be implemented as criteria and sub-criteria linked via the property cccev:hasRequirement pointing to a requirement of type cccev:Criterion. Examples of sub requirements of different nature can a criterion that defines different types of information requirements (e.g. evidences to support the responses to the criterion) and establishing constraints (e.g. input parameters, thresholds, or other types of restrictions).
